\begin_layout Standard
This change in agriculture will require a new influx of farmers with new
 ideas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One possible consequence of this change is that the price of agricultural
 products increases.
 But this is only the case if the social costs are not taken into account.
 If these were to fall significantly, wouldn't society be better off? However,
 getting this message across is very difficult as we have seen in France
 with the Yellow Rashes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Meino Smit makes the case that if there had been a policy in 1950 that took
 all costs into account, we would be better off now.
 Breeding has caused an output increase of 20 to 25%.
 Partly because of this and through innovation that would have focused more
 on better working conditions with less use of energy and raw materials,
 for example through improved hand tools, agriculture could have achieved
 an output increase that was greater than today without the hallucinatory
 increase in input.
 Agriculture would have been more robust and there would be more farmers
 and greater social support.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Has my dream changed?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My goal in starting the training is to bring the system of Ferme du Bec
 Hellouin to Flanders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through the study work around this paper, it has become clear that there
 is a real need for agriculture that repairs the damage done.
 We have seen that kitchen gardens and especially the Chinese agriculture
 of 1930 can be great sources of inspiration here.
 The system of Ferme du Bec Hellouin uses the same principles of combined
 cultivation, intense follow-up, high input of organic fertilizers combined
 with not disturbing the soil, permanent cover and many other factors to
 optimize the natural processes.
\end_layout

